---
title: "The HALO Effect"
author: "Kevin Kwok"
domain: "kwokchain.com"
url: "https://kwokchain.com/2025/07/15/the-halo-effect/"
pubDate: 2025-03-09
takeaway: "Explores a new class of network/aggregation dynamics and their implications for platform defensibility."
---

Kevin Kwok's analysis of what he terms the "HALO effect" introduces a fascinating lens for looking at modern platform defensibility. In an era where traditional data network effects are increasingly commoditized by foundational AI models, we have to look deeper for sustainable competitive advantage. Kwok argues that there is a fresh breed of network and aggregation dynamics at play that goes beyond simple two-sided matching or data accumulation. It is about how different nodes, interactions, and ancillary products on a platform create a halo of value that reinforces the core transactions, making it almost impossible for users to untangle themselves or for competitors to find a clean entry point.

As a founder trying to architect a modern SaaS or platform company, this makes me deeply reflect on our own product boundaries. It is not enough to just build a great tool that links buyers and sellers, or users and data. We have to map out the secondary and tertiary loops—how a user's workflow in one part of our software naturally feeds into and illuminates another user's experience elsewhere. This level of complexity is harder to build, but it creates the kind of organic, multi-layered defensibility that simple feature parity cannot touch. It challenges us to design for systemic emergence rather than just linear utility.

### What stuck with me

* **Systemic platform defensibility**: True defensibility in modern markets relies on complex, overlapping product loops rather than simple single-layer network effects.
* **Dynamic user value**: The interactions between secondary and primary workflows on a platform can create an emergent utility that is highly sticky.
* **Architecting for emergence**: Engineering teams should design systems that allow data and workflows to naturally cross-pollinate and reinforce other areas of the platform.
